title: TV picks for the week of Oct. 11 | Entertainment News
text:
Now we're talking (but only during the commercials, please). "Fargo" and "The Walking Dead" are among this week's highly anticipated television returns. Here's what else caught my eye:
Sunday: "America's Funniest Home Videos," 6 p.m., ABC: Cover your crotches -- the new season kicks (literally) off tonight.
"The Walking Dead," 8 p.m., AMC: Season 6 begins with a 90-minute premiere.
"Talking Dead," 9:30 p.m., AMC: I swear, if Rick Grimes were a baseball pitcher instead of a cop, AMC would start an after-show called "The Balking Dead."
Monday: "Fargo," 9 p.m., FX: The follow-up to last season's terrific run takes place in 1979.
Tuesday: "Mary Tyler Moore: A Celebration," 7 p.m., PBS: Who can turn your TV on with her smile? Sorry, not even Mary -- you'll still have to use your remote.
"Secrets of the Dead," 8 p.m., PBS: Historians seek the truth about the Trojan horse.
"Manhattan," 8 p.m., WGN America: Season 2 begins.
"Chicago Fire," 9 p.m., NBC: Where's the fire? Back for a fourth season, that's where.
Wednesday: "Nature," 7 p.m., PBS: Wildlife filmmakers present elephant footage from Botswana.
"The Brain with Dr. David Eagleman," 9 p.m., PBS: On AMC, this would be a zombie show.
Thursday: "Nathan For You," 9 p.m., Comedy Central: Season 3 begins.
"Late Night Chef Fight," 9 p.m., FYI: Bone-in elk and pigskin are on the second-season premiere's plate.
Friday: "Jessie," 7 p.m., Disney Channel: Christina comes home and Jessie heads to Los Angeles in tonight's series finale.
"Truth Be Told," 7:30 p.m., NBC: Another sitcom? There goes the neighborhood.
"Ghost Asylum," 8 p.m., Destination America: The channel scares up a new season.
"Gold Rush," 8 p.m., Discovery: Season 6 begins.
"Live From Lincoln Center," 8 p.m., PBS: This production of Kern and Hammerstein's "Show Boat" is based on the original 1927 score and includes rarely heard tunes.
"Play It Forward," 8 p.m., Showtime: This documentary tells the story of legendary NFL tight end Tony Gonzalez and his brother Chris.
"The Knick," 9 p.m., Cinemax: The acclaimed drama kicks off its second season.
"Neighborhood Sessions: Toby Keith," 9 p.m., TBS: The country crooner performs in his Oklahoma hometown.
"Satisfaction," 9 p.m., USA: Season 2 begins.
Saturday: "They Found Hell," 8 p.m., Syfy: Coeds find a portal to H-E-double-you-know-where.
"Amy Schumer: Live from the Apollo," 9 p.m., HBO: Chris Rock directs the hot comic's standup special.
